about:
Zǒng Shì Qí, (總是騎); también conocido como Khenpo Tsultrim, ( མཁན་པོ་ ཚུལ་ཁྲིམས་ ) estudió el budismo zen y tibetano. 2 años (Línjì disciplina 臨濟 宗) Rinzai Chán (Zen) en Taiwán; 7 años en el monasterio Bokar, India y otros 3 años en los monasterios adicionales de Nepal. Uniendo el dominio y los dones de la doctrina de Vajrayāna (རྡོ་ རྗེ་ ཐེག་ together) junto con Chan (Mahayana). Un Arahant o Boddhisatva reconocido en cada escuela. Únete a mi grupo de discusión "Shantideva and the Boddhisatva Discussion" 

Zǒng Shì Qí, (總是騎) also known as Khenpo Tsultrim, ( མཁན་པོ་ ཚུལ་ཁྲིམས་ ) has studied both Zen and Tibetan Buddhism. 2 years (Línjì discipline 臨濟 宗) Rinzai Chán (Zen) in Taiwan; 7 years in the Bokar Monastery, India and another 3 years in the additional monasteries of Nepal. Uniting the domain and gifts of the doctrine of Vajrayāna (རྡོ་ རྗེ་ ཐེག་ པ་) together with Chan (Mahayana). A recognised Arahant or Boddhisatva in each school. Join my discussion group "Shantideva and the Boddhisatva Discussion " group.

Zac is a composer from Melbourne, Australia. His solid foundation of classical Suzuki piano, music study at school and university, and experience gained over a period of over 15 years has expanded into other music genres from contemporary pop/rock to ambient and experimental styles.

Zac’s personal interest and experience of meditation resulted in a collaboration with Jo Ablett, psychotherapist, to create music to support visualisation meditations for children on the album “In My Quiet Body”.  

Zac’s most recent album, Fireflies, was written as a purely instrumental album for a more universal application - as non distracting background music for therapy sessions, or simply as relaxation, sleeping or meditation music.  The piano pieces follow a natural rhythm with an ebb and flow, intended to match the breath and body, ease the mind and set the scene for peaceful relaxation.  Fireflies has been successfully applied in therapeutic use, in school classrooms, settling babies, young people and adults for sleep and as calming background music. ...read more

This all started centuries or even millennia ago, long before the industrial age, when there was no entertainment industry, when everything was 100% organic. This original heavy metal music was not just background music at ancient temples, nor entertainment for royalty; it appears that brain/mind entrainment into deeper states, and dis-entrainment into the "state of no state" facilitated by the complex, rich, textured harmonics and sub-harmonic beats was intentional. It is quite likely that exploration of the resulting states and non-states was a facet of the spiritual, for lack of better words, training and education; that the sounds acted as guides or stepping stones to making non-ordinary states become more ordinary, at least to those who practiced. And as we, through our ancestors, have heard sounds of natural, acoustic instruments for centuries or even millennia, there is something innately familiar, even sacred, about the sound of these and other antique musical instruments.

Much, maybe most music is about communicating a message of sorts, usually emotional, the dance of the mating ritual in various permutations, we know the stories. 33 Bowls does not directly do that, the intention is holding the space to facilitate and enhance whatever is present. What it is doing is providing a coherent, yet complex natural “signal” for the ears/ brain/mind/heart/CNS to entrain to and “drop” into a more relaxed, lower stress state of being. Our ears are not passive; they are active participants in sound, interacting with the environment in a way which leads to brain/mind entrainment with what we hear, whether it is shamanic drums, singing bowls, the cacophony of city noise, or the breath and heartbeat of someone close to us.

Deep Gratitude to countless generations of Artisans who listened to the Grand Muse; who practiced, even mastered the Art of expressing the resonance and coherence of the Universal Aum; who crafted these and other Singing Bowls.

Your memory lives on. ...read more

​Dr. Mao Shing Ni was ordained as the Head of the Integral Way Tradition in 2000. He oversees the College of Tao and is active in teaching the Path of a Constructive Life—the attainment of physical, mental, spiritual, moral and financial health in one’s life.

He is also co-founder and co-chancellor of Yo San University in Los Angeles.  He is currently director and a professor of Chinese medicine at Yo San University. 

Dr. Mao is a Licensed Acupuncturist, a Diplomate of Chinese Herbology and a Diplomate in Anti-Aging. He is currently in general practice with special interest in immune, hormonal and aging related conditions. He was awarded the Outstanding Acupuncturist of the Year Award in 1987.  Dr. Mao is a member of the American Academy of Anti-Aging Medicine, the AOM ALLIANCE, American Society of Acupuncturist, the American Association of Acupuncturist & Oriental Medicine and National certification Commission for Acupuncturist & Oriental Medicine Diplomate in Chinese Herbology.
